subject: ASIAN DAILY ECONOMIC RELEASE CALENDAR IS NOW AVAILABLE IN THE RESEARCH SECTION OF THE WEBSITE: Highlights include Japanese GDP and Chinese Lending/Financing Data
DAILY ASIA-PAC OPENING NEWS
content:
ASIA-PAC

NEC Director Kudlow said a China deal is still close and talks have been constructive, while he added that US President Trump likes what he sees in US-China trade talks but is not ready to sign any trade deal with China and that there is no single condition that would make or break the talks right now when asked about what China needs to do to avoid 15 December tariffs. Kudlow also stated that Hong Kong issues has not spilled over into trade talks just yet and that talks are now around the clock but stated he doesn’t know of any plans for US negotiators to travel for talks right now and there are no face to face talks currently scheduled between US President Trump and China President Xi. (Newswires)

China top diplomat Yang spoke with US Secretary of State Pompeo on Saturday in which he stated the US has seriously violated international relations by passing the Hong Kong and Uighur bills, while he urged US to correct its mistakes and immediately stop interfering with China’s internal affairs. (Newswires)

China has reportedly taken countermeasures against US limit on diplomats according to sources citing Chinese media, while there were separate reports the President of the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong Tara Joseph was denied entry into Macau after being detained for 2 hours. (Newswires)

China ordered government offices and public institutions to remove foreign computer equipment and software. (Newswires)

China Global Times editorial noted that China does not need to compete with the tough attitude from the US and should be proud of surpassing the US in tenacity, strategy and manoeuvrability. (Newswires)

  • Chinese Exports (USD)(Nov) Y/Y -1.1% vs. Exp. 1.0% (Prev. -0.9%)
  • Chinese Imports (USD)(Nov) Y/Y 0.3% vs. Exp. -1.8% (Prev. -6.4%)

  • New Zealand Manufacturing Sales (Q3) -0.3% (Prev. -2.7%)

 

UK/EU

UK Election Panelbase poll: Conservatives 43% (+1), Labour 34% (unch), Lib Dems 13% (Unch.), Brexit Party 3% (-1), taken December 4th-6th. (Newswires)

UK Election BMG Research poll: Conservatives 41% (+2), Labour 32% (-1), Lib Dems 14% (+1), Brexit Party 4% (Unch.), taken December 4th-6th. (Newswires)

UK Election YouGov poll: Conservatives 43% (+1), Labour 33% (unch), Lib Dems 13% (+1), Brexit Party 3% (-1), taken December 5th-6th. (Newswires)

DataPraxis MRP Model suggest Conservatives will win 344 seats (+27), Labour 221 (-41), Lib Dems 14 (+2), SNP 47 (+12). (Newswires)

Fitch affirmed Sweden at 'AAA', Outlook Stable. (Newswires)

 

FX

BoC Governor Poloz is to step down when his term expires in June 2020. (Newswires)

Canadian Employment Change (Nov) -71.2k vs. Exp. 10.0k (Prev. -1.8k). (Newswires) Canadian Unemployment Rate (Nov) 5.9% vs. Exp. 5.5% (Prev. 5.5%)

 

COMMODITIES

Baker Hughes Rig Count: Oil rigs -5 at 663, Nat gas +2 at 133, total rigs -4 at 799; drillers cut rigs for the 7th consecutive week. (Newswires)

Saudi Energy Minister Abdulaziz said they will continue the voluntary cut of 400k bpd and that the country will cut output by a further 167k bpd, while he also suggested the jury is still out on where the oil market will be in March and that there are 2 conditions before raising output which are lower global inventories and price backwardation. Saudi’s Energy Minister also said that they will not unilaterally raise output to punish non-complying nations and wants to see global inventories close to 2010-2014 averages, while he added that Saudi is committed to continued cooperation with Russia beyond March 2020 and expects oil output resumption from the joint fields soon although it will not impact the OPEC cut. (Newswires)

Russian Energy Minister Novak said OPEC+ are to cut additionally 500k BPD in Q1 in line with recommendations yesterday and that Russia's oil quota will be 300k excluding gas condensate. (Newswires)

Iranian Oil Minister said around half a million of new cuts have been agreed to and suggested there will be an extraordinary OPEC meeting in the next three or four months, according to Twitter reports. (Twitter)

Venezuela government and opposition are reportedly considering providing private oil companies operating rights including Chevron (CVX), Rosneft and CNPC, although PDVSA would hold a majority stake according to sources. (Newswires)

 

GEOPOLITICS

Senior US State Department official Schenker said the US is readying further sanctions over the killing of protesters in Iraq and stated there is a strong chance Iran is behind the attack on Iraq's Balad Air base but more evidence is needed, while the State Department also stated there will be further sanctions on Iran in the future. (Newswires)

Turkish Defense Minister said there was no agreement reached at NATO and that Turkey was left alone in the fight against terror". (Newswires)

 

US

  • US Non-Farm Payrolls (Nov) 266k vs. Exp. 180.0k (Prev. 128.0k, Rev. 156k); two-month net revisions +41k (Prev. +95k). (Newswires)
  • US Unemployment Rate (Nov) 3.5% vs. Exp. 3.6% (Prev. 3.6%)
  • US Average Earnings (Nov) Y/Y 3.1% vs. Exp. 3.0% (Prev. 3.0%, Rev. 3.2%)

 

MARKET RECAP

Amazon (AMZN) saw some slight downside after WSJ reported US President Trump was considering adding the company’s foreign sites to a notorious market list, which is a list of global marketplaces known for counterfeit goods. Goldman Sachs (GS) caught a bid after reports its 1Malaysia Development Bhd (1MDB) fine is likely to be under USD 2bln, a sum lower than what some analysts suggested the bank would have to pay for allegedly misleading investors over bond sales totalling USD 6.5bln that the bank helped raise for the sovereign wealth fund (1MDB). Tesla (TSLA) up just shy of 2% after China made Tesla cars qualify for subsidies where buyers will get as much as USD 3550 from the government. Uber (UBER) traded in the red after it released its statistics which saw 3000 sexual assault claims last year and in total it saw 107 total fatalities. Its sexual assault statistics showed one in 2mln trips saw non-consensual kissing of a non-sexual body part, where 1 in 3mln saw non-consensual kissing of a sexual body part. DR Horton (DHI) traded lower after a sell initiation from Goldman Sachs with a USD 51 price target and Ciena (CIEN) were lower by over 4% after a downgrade to sell from neutral at UBS. SPX +0.9% at 3,145.90; Dow +1.2% at 28,009.83; NDX +1.1% at 8,397.39.

Yields are higher between 4-5bps across the curve, the the TPLEX seeing selling pressure in wake of a solid jobs report for November, where the headline surprised to the upside. Additionally, prelim consumer confidence data from the UoM was firmer than expected. Next week, the Fed is expected to stand pat on rates, and according to market pricing, as derived from the CME's Fedwatch tool, there is a 100% chance of an unchanged decision (which was priced with 99.3% certainty on Thursday). Ahead of the US day, constructive news on the trade front (China plans to implement tariff waivers for some purchases of US ags, and will begin applications for importing soybeans and pork from the US) resulted in some downside for Treasuries. There was also reports of short-covering after remarks from NEC director Kudlow (tariffs are up to the President), while other reports suggested short-covering came ahead of next week's FOMC and ECB confabs. Major curve spreads, however, are little changed, though 2s5s and 2s10s are up by around 1bps at settlement, and 2s30s 5s10s 5s30s and 10s30s a touch narrower). T-notes (H0) settled 13+ ticks lower at 128-28+.
